P2. Investigate a Dataset¶

Introduction¶

The task is to explore a provided dataset in order to get some interesting insights, and I chose the Sean Lahman's baseball database as the source of data.

I picked it over other options because it looks like something not many people have looked into (Titanic dataset seems to be much more popular), and also since I've been impressed by the story of Billy Beane, who was the first to apply statistical analysis to the players' data in order to evaluate them.

This became known as "sabermetrics" and the whole story was popularized later via a book and a movie "Moneyball".

Being a non-american, I also don't have much clue about baseball, so it's a nice opportunity to learn about the sport.

Questions to the data¶

Ideally, one would hope to repeat Billy Beane's success and find how player/team performance correlates with different attributes.

But since we yet don't know much about those attributes, let's explore the data first.

Data exploration¶

Let's start from the top-down view of the data, and then proceed with drilling into more details.

Let's print the head and statistics for each table.

In [3]:
import pandas as pd

tables = {}
for f in files:
    name = f.split('.')[0]
    tables[name] = pd.read_csv(dir_root + f)

HEADER_FORMAT = '<hr/><h4 style="color:steelblue;">{}</h4>'    
def show_table_header(title):
    disp.display(disp.HTML(HEADER_FORMAT.format(title)))
    
for name in sorted(tables.keys()):
    table = tables[name]
    show_table_header(name)
    disp.display('{} rows'.format(len(table)))
    disp.display(table.head(), table.describe())

Looking at the above, together with the readme file, some first observations:

The main table with player (and manager) data, called Master, with the primary key playerID (used in other tables to reference the player), contains data about all players:

  • Name
  • Birth date and death date (if applicable)
  • Birth Country/State/City
  • Weight and height
  • First and final game dates
  • Player batting and throwing hand (left, right or both)

Other interesting tables are:

  • Salaries - what looks like a yearly salary in dollars, keyed by the playerID, together with the year/team/league of playing. One can ask many interesting questions involving player salaries.
  • Batting, Pitching, Fielding - corresponding detailed statistics for players, by year, team etc. This is where the "meat" of the data is, presumably allowing us to compute player performance according to both the traditional methods and sabermetrics. That computed performance can be correlated with things like team wins, salary etc.
  • Managers - data about team managers. How many team losses, wins and whether the manager is a former player.
  • Teams - team performance by year (teams are keyed by teamID)
  • Appearances - shows in which team and which roles the players appeared
  • CollegePlaying/Schools - allow to see which players started their career playing in college teams
  • AwardsManagers/AwardsPlayers - awards, won by managers and players

Remark about the data cleaning¶

The data already nicely organized into a tabular shape, with primary keys being unique etc.:

In [4]:
def check_unique(table_name, column_name):
    t = tables[table_name][column_name]
    print('Table {}, column {} is {}unique!'.format(
        table_name, column_name, '' if t.nunique() == len(t) else 'NOT '))

PRIMARY_KEYS = [
    ('Master', 'playerID'),
    ('Schools', 'schoolID')
]

for t, c in PRIMARY_KEYS:
    check_unique(t, c)

Table Master, column playerID is unique!
Table Schools, column schoolID is unique!

...which is rather expected, given that these CSV files where presumably created via export from a relational database.

Some more things about the data to keep in mind:

  • There is a lot of missing data (which pandas shows as NaN), almost for every column. This is the case for all the tables. The missing data should be gracefully skipped from the computations, where applicable.

  • In some cases missing data is not necessarily represented by a NaN, but can be also e.g. a zero value (such as in Salaries table).

  • Should be also mindful about things like inflation over the years when making computations with salaries, so that apples are compared to apples.

  • The Master table seems to have not only player data, but also managers' as well, even though not many things hint about that

Looking closer at the data and asking the questions¶

Based only on the Master table, there may already be some curious things to look at:

  • Player origin distribution
  • Weight/height statistics for baseball players, as compared with population median
  • Horoscope signs distribution among the player (rather useless knowledge, but why not)

Further, the strategy may be to pull in extra aggregate attributes into the Master table (e.g. from Salaries, CollegePlaying, AwardsPlayers tables) and ask more questions based on that.

In [5]:
MASTER = tables['Master']

def parse_state(line):
    name, abbr, pop = line.strip().split(',')
    return (name, abbr, int(pop))

state_pop = pd.DataFrame(

state_data = state_pop.merge(player_counts, on='abbr', how='left')

Does playing in a college league matter?¶

One assumption is that Washington D.C. may have more colleges per capita, which means more possibilities for talented people to start eventually playing baseball professionally, by jumpstarting their carreer at a college baseball league.

Conveniently, we have tables CollegePlaying and Schools, so we can accept or reject the null hypothesis H0:

H0: There is no monotonic correlation between:

  • number of Major League players born in a state and
  • number of Major League players starting career in a home state's college

(we take a confidence interval of 95%, i.e. $\alpha=0.05$)

Additionally, we can extract a total number of colleges from an external data source:

In [10]:
state_colleges = pd.read_csv('data/colleges.csv', sep=';', header=0)
state_data = state_data.merge(state_colleges, on='abbr', how='left')

Now do a three-way join between Master, Schools and CollegePlaying tables to find a total number of years that professional players may have spen playing in a college from their birth state:

In [11]:
birth_state_college_years = tables['CollegePlaying']\
    .merge(MASTER, on='playerID')\
    .merge(tables['Schools'], left_on=['schoolID', 'birthState'], 
           right_on=['schoolID', 'state'])\
    .groupby(by='playerID', as_index=False)['yearID'].count()\
    .rename(columns={'yearID': 'yearsAtBirthStateCollege'})
MASTER = MASTER.merge(birth_state_college_years, on='playerID', how='left')
In [12]:
state_data = MASTER[['yearsAtBirthStateCollege', 'birthState']]\
    .groupby('birthState').count().reset_index()\
    .merge(state_data, how='right', left_on='birthState', right_on='abbr')\
    .sort_values('playersBorn', ascending=False)
state_data['homeCollegePlayersPer1M'] = 1e6*state_data['yearsAtBirthStateCollege']/state_data['population']
state_data['numInstitutionsPer1M'] = 1e6*state_data['numInstitutions']/state_data['population']
In [13]:
def corr_plot(df, v1, v2):    
    ax = sns.jointplot(v1, v2, data=df, kind="reg", 
                       scatter_kws=dict(s=100, color="steelblue"), stat_func=stats.spearmanr)
    ax.plot_joint(sns.kdeplot, n_levels=5)
    
corr_plot(state_data, 'playersPer1M', 'homeCollegePlayersPer1M')

Spearman rank-order correlation coefficient is 0.66, which suggests strong correlation between the two variables.

The value of $p$ is way smaller than our $\alpha=0.05$, which means that we reject the hypothesis H0, and there is a significant correlation between playing in a college of a home state and becoming a Major League baseball player.

What about total number of institutions vs players born in the state (the initial assumption)?

In [14]:
corr_plot(state_data, 'playersPer1M', 'numInstitutionsPer1M')

There is some correlation, but it can not be accepted as statistically significant ($p>0.05$), therefor we would not reject H0 for these two variables.

This could mean that distribution of the colleges that have baseball leagues is not that uniform between different states.

Interestingly, in both cases a prominent outlier is the very Washington D.C.

What zodiac signs are represented most?¶

This one is pointless, but amusing nevertheless, so let's enhance out Master table with a Zodiac sign for every player/manager:

In [15]:
zodiac = pd.read_csv('data/zodiac.csv', sep=';', header=0)

def get_sign(master_row):
    month, day = master_row[['birthMonth', 'birthDay']]
    if np.isnan(month) or np.isnan(day):
        return np.NaN
    for _, s, ds, ms, de, me in zodiac.itertuples():
        if (month == ms and day >= ds) or \
           (month == me and day <= de) or \
           (ms < month < me):
            return s
    return np.NaN

MASTER['zodiacSign'] = MASTER.apply(get_sign, axis=1)
pc = MASTER['zodiacSign'].value_counts()
zodiac = zodiac.merge(pd.DataFrame({'sign':pc.index, 'playersOfSign':pc.values}), 
                      on='sign', how='left')

zodiac['playersOfSign%'] = zodiac['playersOfSign'].div(
    zodiac['playersOfSign'].sum()).multiply(100)
zodiac.sort_values(['playersOfSign'], ascending=False).head()

What we can see is the distribution is rather not about Virgo in particular, but rather about time of the year the baseball players were born: late summer and early autumn.

And apparently, there exists an explanation to this phenomena:

The magical date of Aug. 1 gives a strong hint as to the explanation for this phenomenon. For more than 55 years, July 31 has been the age-cutoff date used by virtually all nonschool-affiliated baseball leagues in the United States. Youth baseball organizations including Little League, Cal Ripken/Babe Ruth, PONY, Dixie Youth, Hap Dumont, Dizzy Dean, American Legion, and more have long used that date to determine which players are eligible for which levels of play.

In [17]:
def plot_scatter_trend(df, col_x, col_y, title):
    s = df[[col_x, col_y]].dropna().sort_values([col_x])

    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 6))
    plt.suptitle(title, fontsize=20)
    plt.rcParams['xtick.major.pad'] = 8
    sx = s[col_x]
    sy = s[col_y]
    ax = plt.plot(sx, sy, '.', linestyle='None', markevery=1)

    z = np.polyfit(sx, sy, 1)
    p = np.poly1d(z)
    plt.plot(sx, p(sx), "b--")
    plt.xlabel(col_x, fontsize=13)
    plt.ylabel(col_y, fontsize=13)
    

plot_scatter_trend(MASTER, 'birthYear', 'weight', "Players' weight by birth year, pounds")
plot_scatter_trend(MASTER, 'birthYear', 'height', "Players' height by birth year, inches")

plot_scatter_trend(MASTER, 'birthYear', 'lifeLength', "Players' life length by birth year, years")

In [20]:
cpi = pd.read_csv('data/cpi.csv', sep=';', header=0)

def get_cpi(year):
    return float(cpi[cpi['year'] == year]['cpi'])

def get_adjusted_dollar_value(price, price_year, adjusted_year):
    cpip = get_cpi(price_year)
    cpia = get_cpi(adjusted_year)
    return 1.0*price*cpia/cpip

YEAR = 2017
def index_row(row):
    return get_adjusted_dollar_value(row['salary'], row['yearID'], YEAR)

SALARIES['salaryIndexed'] = SALARIES.apply(index_row, axis=1)
In [21]:
plot_scatter_trend(SALARIES, 'yearID', 'salaryIndexed', "Players' indexed salary USD/year")

STATS = [
    # central tendency:
    ['Mean', np.mean], ['Median', np.median], ['Trimmed mean (10%)', lambda x: stats.trim_mean(x, .1)], 
    # variability:
    ['Standard deviation', np.std], 
    ['First quartile', np.percentile, 25], ['Third quartile', np.percentile, 75],
    ['Interquartile range', lambda x: np.percentile(x, 75) - np.percentile(x, 25)],
    ['5% percentile', np.percentile, 5], ['95% percentile', np.percentile, 95],
    # other:
    ['Min', np.amin], ['Max', np.amax], ['Count', len]]

def gather_stats(col):
    return [desc[1](col.dropna(), *desc[2:]) for desc in STATS]

def display_stats(series_dict):
    df = pd.DataFrame(list(map(gather_stats, series_dict.values())), 
             index = series_dict.keys(), columns = [x[0] for x in STATS])
    disp.display(df.T)

Conclusion¶

We only took a peek into the historical baseball data, but there is much more to see there.

This particular dataset has many dimensions and spans a long period of time, so one can ask many interesting questions to the data.

And the data may reveal some exciting stories about the history of baseball, the nature of sport, personal dramas and many more.

One has to remember, however, that the data should also be questioned - many entries are incomplete or downright wrong, so all these stories should be a subject to a careful eye.

And of course, never forget about the fundamental things, such as correlation is not causation, and one example of this was a seemengly prevalent zodiac sign of Virgo among the baseball players (which nevertheless had more realistic, albeit less romantic, explanation).

An interesting observation is that it's only during the later years we've got such a powerful and accessible tools for computation and data visualization, like Python with variety of all kinds of libraries, not even mentioning wide availability of computational power, data sources and knowledge thanks to the Internet.

Maybe, if these tools were available earlier, there would be less drama and confusion around the techniques regarding the players evaluation (which gave birth to the techniques like sabermetrics and "Moneyball"), since it would be much easier to look into the data.

But then, sport in general, and baseball is particular is all about the drama. That's what makes it exciting!

Limitations¶

Most of the computations were made on incomplete data, which in many cases severely limited the sample sizes (for example, salary data is only available starting from year 1985, and even then it's far from being complete).

Another rather serious problem with above computations is that it uses Master table as the source of players data, ignoring the fact that some of the entries in the table belong to non-player managers, thus skewing some of the results.
